You can animate the opacity of images with `.each()` iterator function:

      $(&#39;.lookdown img&#39;).each(function() {
        $(this).delay(delay).animate({
          opacity: 1
        }, 500);
        delay += 500;
      });

https://jsfiddle.net/ow0Lu21h/

Try this:

```
var delay = 0;
var pace = 1000;  // 1 second
  $(&#39;.lookdown img&#39;).each(function() {
    $(this).delay(delay).animate({
      opacity: 1
    }, pace);
    delay += pace;
  });
```

With the approach of delayed animations over a image loop you will run into a lot of problems and edge cases, mostly because of the option to reverse the animation. Easiest way to avoid all potential issues is to use a different animation principle: By working with a window interval and constantly asking for the current animation direction, you can ensure the animation integrity. 

In my code I am working with timeouts, which will give you the chance to have a much faster polling interval when the animation is paused - but while it is running, it always waits for a transition to complete before changing direction.

    var intv = function() {
      if(direction === 0) return window.setTimeout(intv, interval);
      var next = position + direction &lt; 0 ? images.length - 1 : position + direction &gt;= images.length ? 0 : position + direction;
      $(images[position]).fadeOut(transition);
      $(images[next]).fadeIn(transition);
      position = next;
      return window.setTimeout(intv, showtime + transition);
    };

https://jsfiddle.net/jdx0zufa/

You can change this code to different behaviors by just changing the `next` calculation - e.g. when it has reached the end and is running forward, change the direction to backward, etc.

