This is a slightly different approach, but instead of writing separate methods for each input (like Name, Age, Height, etc), another option is to create helper methods that takes in a string used to prompt the user for input, and then return a strongly typed value back to the caller.

For strings it&#39;s quite simple:

    private static string GetStringFromUser(string prompt)
    {
        Console.Write(prompt);
        return Console.ReadLine();
    }

But for other types, like a number or a date, we need to validate that the user entered in a string that can be converted. For these types of methods, I use a `do/while` loop, whose condition is the result of a `TryParse` method (which return a `bool` indicating whether or not a string was successfully converted to the type, and which take an `out` parameter of that type that gets set to the converted value).

I also added an optional &quot;validator&quot; argument, which allows the caller to specify some additional constraints in the form of a method that takes in an argument of the specified type and returns a bool indicating whether or not the argument is valid (like if the age entered must be greater than 16 and less than 100, for example). I used an inline lambda expression in the example at the bottom, but you could pass the name of a method as well.

Here&#39;s one for getting an integer from the user:

    private static int GetIntFromUser(string prompt, Func&lt;int, bool&gt; validator = null)
    {
        int result;
        var cursorTop = Console.CursorTop;

        do
        {
            ClearSpecificLineAndWrite(cursorTop, prompt);
        } while (!int.TryParse(Console.ReadLine(), out result) ||
                 !(validator?.Invoke(result) ?? true));

        return result;
    }

    private static void ClearSpecificLineAndWrite(int cursorTop, string message)
    {
        Console.SetCursorPosition(0, cursorTop);
        Console.Write(new string(&#39; &#39;, Console.WindowWidth));
        Console.SetCursorPosition(0, cursorTop);
        Console.Write(message);
    }

Now, with methods like these, we can do this:

    string userName = GetStringFromUser(&quot;Enter your name: &quot;);
    int userAge = GetIntFromUser(&quot;How old are you (16-100): &quot;, x =&gt; x &gt;= 16 &amp;&amp; x &lt;= 10);

